Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C and pop in the #baking trays{} to get hot. Remove the @Northern Dough Co. Pizza Dough{2} from your fridge and allow it to come to room temperature. Halve, then remove the cores from the @orange pepper{1}, @yellow pepper{1/2} and @red pepper{1} and cut into ½cm wide slices. Halve, peel and slice the @echalion shallot{1/2} into thin half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain the @mozzarella{1}, slice into 1cm thick rounds and pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

Pick the @basil{1/2}(finely chopped) leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). In a #mixing bowl{}, combine half the @?basil{1/2} with the @tomato passata{1/2} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. This is your pizza sauce.

Cut the @streaky bacon rasher{4} into 1cm thick slices. Put a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Cook the bacon until it begins to brown, ~{3%minutes}. Add the peppers and shallot. Cook until the veggies have softened, ~{7-8%minutes}. Add the garlic and remaining basil and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Remove the pan from the heat and set aside. This is your calzone filling.

If you have some @flour{}, lightly dust your work surface or else put the dough between two sheets of #clingfilm{}. Roll each dough ball into a circle the size of a dinner plate, roughly ½cm thick. Spread a tablespoon of pizza sauce onto each pizza base, leaving a 2cm border around the edge. Pile the filling onto one half of each pizza base then lay on the mozzarella. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

To make the calzones, run a wet finger around the border of each pizza base, fold over the uncovered half and press the edges down. Roll the edges back over on themselves to seal tightly. Remove your hot #baking trays{} from the oven and carefully transfer the calzones. Poke a hole in the top of each with a small, sharp #knife{} - this allows the steam to escape! Bake on the top shelf of your oven for ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, chop the @vine tomatoes{1} into wedges and put in a #large bowl{}. Add the @baby leaves{1}. Drizzle over the @balsamic vinegar{1} and @olive oil{1}. When the calzones are cooked, carefully remove them from the oven and serve one per person with some salad alongside. Enjoy!

> At the Fresh Farm we get pretty excited about pizza. We're partial to a pie, too. But a pizza-pie hybrid? The deliciousness is almost overwhelming! As a folded pizza, the calzone combines the best of both worlds. Its name comes from the Italian word for 'trouser-leg' or 'stocking', so called because it's stuffed full of good things. Cook it first this week so you enjoy the dough at its freshest.